<doc id="205780" wikidata="Q5968748" url="?curid=205780" title="T. J. Bass (author)">
<text>Thomas J. Bassler (July 7, 1932 – December 13, 2011), who used the pseudonym T. J. Bass, was an American science fiction author and physician, having graduated from the University of Iowa in 1959. Bassler is also known for his controversial claim that nonsmokers who are able to complete a marathon in under four hours can eat whatever they wish and never suffer a fatal heart attack.
John Robbins has noted that Jim Fixx approvingly quoted Bassler in his best-selling book, &quot;The Complete Book of Running&quot;. Fixx died from heart failure at 52 while running.

Two of Bass&#x27; novels, &quot;Half Past Human&quot; (1971) and &quot;The Godwhale&quot; (1974), were nominated for the Nebula Award. In both his books the Hive was a three trillion population of &#x27;nebishes&#x27; - humans who had four toes and all aggressiveness bred out of them.

==Bibliography==
Science fiction novels &quot;(as T. J. Bass)&quot;
*&quot;Half Past Human&quot; (1971, fix-up)
*&quot;The Godwhale&quot; (1974)
